# Hometown Hero Banner Management System - Configuration File
# 
# This file contains environment variable settings for configuring data paths.
# Place this file in one of these locations:
#   1. In the repository root (for single-user deployments)
#   2. In an external directory and set HH_CONFIG_DIR to point to it
#
# Example shared drive deployment:
#   1. Create: Q:\HHBanners2026-data\.env
#   2. Set environment variable: set HH_CONFIG_DIR=Q:\HHBanners2026-data
#   3. Or configure scripts\run_app.bat to set DATA_DIR

# Database Path
# Default: ./hometown_hero.db (in repository directory)
# Example Windows: Q:\HHBanners2026-data\hometown_hero.db
# Example Linux/Mac: /mnt/shared/hh-data/hometown_hero.db
HH_DB_PATH=./hometown_hero.db

# Microsoft 365 Email Configuration Path
# Default: ./m365_config.json (in repository directory)
# Example Windows: Q:\HHBanners2026-data\m365_config.json
# Example Linux/Mac: /mnt/shared/hh-data/m365_config.json
HH_M365_CONFIG=./m365_config.json

# Export Directory for Generated Files
# Default: ./exports (in repository directory)
# Example Windows: Q:\HHBanners2026-data\exports
# Example Linux/Mac: /mnt/shared/hh-data/exports
HH_EXPORT_DIR=./exports

# External Configuration Directory (optional)
# When set, the system will look for .env file in this directory
# This allows keeping all configuration and data separate from code
# Example Windows: Q:\HHBanners2026-data
# Example Linux/Mac: /mnt/shared/hh-data
# HH_CONFIG_DIR=

# DEPLOYMENT NOTES:
# 
# For local development:
#   - Leave all paths as defaults (./hometown_hero.db, etc.)
#   - Data stays in your local repository folder
#
# For shared drive deployment:
#   1. Create external data directory (e.g., Q:\HHBanners2026-data)
#   2. Copy this file to that directory
#   3. Update paths above to point to external directory
#   4. Set HH_CONFIG_DIR to external directory OR
#      configure scripts\run_app.bat with DATA_DIR
#
# For multi-user access:
#   - Use external data directory on shared drive
#   - Only ONE user should write to database at a time
#   - Multiple users can read/browse simultaneously
#   - Consider running Streamlit centrally on a server
